<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONRAD J. BAUMGARTNER; SURGEON IN GROUND-BREAKING USE OF TV 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Conrad J. Baumgartner, 91, a surgeon who in 1951 participated in the first 
local closed-circuit color television showing of a surgical procedure. 
Televised from the old General Hospital to the Shrine Auditorium where hundreds 
of doctors were attending meetings of the American Medical Assn. on Dec. 4, 
1951, Baumgartner, then an associate professor of surgery at USC, removed a 
thyroid gland from a patient. It was among the first uses of television as a 
teaching technique in the history of medicine. In Newport Beach on Oct. 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
