<HEADLINE>
<P>
'RAP' VIDEO WEARS AN ORANGE VEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A new "rap" music video featuring television teen heartthrob Richard Grieco 
asks young motorists to drive safely around California Department of 
Transportation highway workers. 
</P>
<P>
"Caltrans workers lay their lives on the line every day just so you can cruise 
through life in the fast lane," says Grieco, star of "Booker" and "21 Jump 
Street" and celebrity spokesman for Caltrans' "Give 'em a Brake" campaign. 
</P>
<P>
Copies of the 4 1/2-minute video, with rap music by "New Choice," a female trio 
from Sacramento which recently signed a recording contract with Warner 
Brothers, were sent to 1,700 California high schools last August for use in 
driver's education classes, Caltrans spokeswoman Tracey Weatherby said. 
</P>
<P>
The video will get its Sacramento premiere Monday night at a comedy club. 
</P>
<P>
Radio and television advertisements based on the video are being produced and 
will be shipped to broadcasters over the next several weeks, she said. 
</P>
<P>
"We wanted to speak to the students in their own language about the dangers of 
highway work," Weatherby said. "Our main message is to respect and protect our 
highway workers and themselves as well. 
</P>
<P>
"Our intention was to speak to them, instead of talking down to them or 
preaching to them," she said. 
</P>
<P>
The "Give 'em a Brake" program was started in 1982 after 19 Caltrans highway 
workers had been killed in 10 years by errant drivers who strayed into the work 
zone. 
</P>
<P>
Since the program's inception seven years ago, five Caltrans workers have been 
killed by motorists. 
</P>
<P>
Weatherby said the new video, developed with the aid of the California Assn. 
for Safety Educators, will help teach a new generation of drivers to look out 
for highway workers. 
</P>
<P>
"We have a captive audience there (in school). They are learning the proper 
procedures of driving. If we can teach them, then we'll have a whole new 
generation of drivers who will respect the people trying to improve the 
conditions of the highway," Weatherby said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
