<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOV. O'NEILL NO LONGER A PRO-CHOICE TARGET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A national abortion rights group Tuesday removed Connecticut Gov. William A. 
O'Neill from a list of top political targets, reversing a stand the group took 
just three days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
The reversal by the National Abortion Rights Action League took O'Neill off a 
list that includes Sen. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.), Florida Gov. Bob Martinez and six 
other elected officials as political targets because of their anti-abortion 
views. 
</P>
<P>
"I have spoken with Gov. O'Neill's office and I have received assurances that 
the governor is not planning any anti-choice initiatives," NARAL leader Kate 
Michelman said. 
</P>
<P>
"The governor has stated that regardless of his own personal views he believes 
individuals have a right to make their own decisions. As a result, NARAL is 
removing him from its list of elected officials targeted for defeat in 1990." 
</P>
<P>
O'Neill said he did not know how he got on the list in the first place, "but 
how I got off there became self-evident because the local people in the state 
of Connecticut knew I shouldn't have been on there to begin with." 
</P>
<P>
Michelman added that her group will be watching all of the candidates in the 
1990 race for Connecticut governor and may "consider involvement" as the 
campaign develops. O'Neill, a Democrat, has said he plans to seek reelection. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Organization for Women launched a tour this week in 
Virginia to encourage women to vote for Democrat Douglas Wilder for governor 
because of the anti-abortion views of his Republican opponent. 
</P>
<P>
Wilder, Virginia's lieutenant governor, faces former Atty. Gen. Marshall 
Coleman on Nov. 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
