<P>
SAN FRANCISCO; 
</P>
<P>
MOUNTAIN LION PROTECTION UPHELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A state Court of Appeal, sharply criticizing Fish and Game officials, refused 
to lift a 17-year ban in California on the killing of mountain lions for sport. 
The three-member panel upheld an order by a San Francisco Superior Court judge 
blocking the proposed hunt until the state Fish and Game Commission more fully 
analyzes the environmental impact of the plan and gives the public more 
information on its consequences. The panel said the commission's environmental 
analysis was "woefully inadequate." State officials, the court said, "chose to 
circulate a document that simply swept the serious criticisms of this project 
under the rug." Spokesmen for the commission and the state attorney general's 
office declined comment, pending study of the panel's opinion, but said an 
appeal to the state Supreme Court will be considered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
