<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARGERS TRADE BANKS, GET NELSON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRIAN HEWITT, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chargers traded linebacker Chip Banks Tuesday and added a running back in 
separate deals that beat the National Football League's trade deadline by less 
than half an hour. 
</P>
<P>
The Chargers sent Banks, who has a history of drug problems, to the 
Indianapolis Colts in a conditional deal that will bring them at least one 1990 
draft pick and maybe more, depending on how well the former USC linebacker 
performs in Indianapolis and whether he remains drug-free. 
</P>
<P>
Banks, 30, recently completed a 90-day drug-treatment program in the San Diego 
area after having been arrested five times in the last 18 months on 
drug-related charges. 
</P>
<P>
Charger owner Alex Spanos had agonized for weeks over whether to give Banks 
another chance with his team after he had publicly said that the five-time Pro 
Bowl player would never play for the Chargers again. 
</P>
<P>
"I've never had this kind of pressure put on me," Spanos said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Spanos finally said that he would allow Banks to return to the Chargers next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
That apparently was not good enough for Banks, who informed the Chargers he 
wanted to play in 1989. They accommodated him by making the trade. 
</P>
<P>
In the other deal, the Chargers acquired veteran Viking running back Darrin 
Nelson from Dallas for a fifth-round pick that the Cowboys immediately shipped 
to the Vikings as a condition of the multi-player deal that sent running back 
Herschel Walker to the Vikings last week. 
</P>
<P>
Nelson, 30, refused to report to Dallas last week after the Walker trade and 
threatened to retire. But he told his agent, Tony Agnone, that there were 
certain teams he would play for if a trade could be arranged. The Chargers were 
one of those teams. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Cowboys also traded holdout quarterback Steve Pelluer to the 
Kansas City Chiefs for a high draft choice in 1990 and 1991. The Cowboys also 
acquired running back Paul Palmer from the Detroit Lions for a 10th-round draft 
choce. 
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Chip Banks 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
