<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: SURGERY TO SIDELINE WOOLRIDGE AT LEAST 3 WEEKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Forward Orlando Woolridge will be out of action a minimum of three weeks after 
bone chips were removed from his right knee during arthroscopic surgery Tuesday 
at Centinela Hospital Medical Center in Inglewood, the Lakers announced. 
</P>
<P>
Woolridge, James Worthy's backup at small forward, will likely miss at least 
the first week of the National Basketball Assn. season, which starts Nov. 3. 
However, the Lakers said they do not expect Woolridge to miss a significant 
portion of the season. 
</P>
<P>
Laker General Manager Jerry West said he was relieved at the result of what 
Laker physician Stephen Lombardo termed diagnostic arthroscopy. The Lakers had 
feared that Woolridge might have suffered cartilage damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101889-0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 122253 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 18, 1989, Wednesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 13; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
394 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATWATCH: WELL-ROUNDED BLACKWELL LIFTS HART'S OFFENSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hart High's Howard Blackwell does not have overwhelming statistics in any 
offensive category, but the senior tailback remains the only area player among 
the top 10 in rushing yardage, receptions and scoring. 
</P>
<P>
Blackwell (5-foot-10, 175 pounds) scored four touchdowns for the second 
consecutive game in Hart's 47-11 rout of Burroughs on Friday. Blackwell's 14 
touchdowns give him 84 points, third among Valley scoring leaders. 
</P>
<P>
He has rushed for 519 yards (ninth) and nine touchdowns in 85 carries (a 
6.1-yard average). He also has caught 21 passes (eighth) for 425 yards and five 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
"I think he's the best back in the Valley," Hart Coach Mike Herrington said. 
"It's just that we're a throwing team and he's not going to get a lot of 
rushing yards." 
</P>
<P>
Defense: Nick Ochoa, a 5-11, 215-pound defensive end at Thousand Oaks, has a 
team-high 14 sacks -- 11 in the past two weeks. Ochoa had seven against Simi 
Valley and added four in a 21-0 win over Camarillo last week. 
</P>
<P>
Canyon defensive back Joe McKeon, in his first varsity start, tied a school 
record with three interceptions against Ridgecrest Burroughs. 
</P>
<P>
Offense: Canyon quarterback Tim Beidle tied a school record with five touchdown 
passes against Ridgecrest Burroughs. 
</P>
<P>
Antelope Valley, which has been outscored, 170-63, this season, has not scored 
in 14 of the past 16 quarters and has been shut out in two of its past three 
games. 
</P>
<P>
Including Friday's shutout, Camarillo has been blanked by Thousand Oaks three 
times in the past five years, scoring only nine points in five games. 
</P>
<P>
Scoring: Monroe kicker Rachel Gagliano, who became the first girl to score a 
point in a City Section varsity football game when she made a conversion kick 
last week, can become the state record-holder among girls if she scores 11 more 
points. Mia Labowitz of San Diego High kicked eight PATs and a 32-yard field 
goal in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
