<HEADLINE>
<P>
AIRPORT HEARINGS POSTPONED AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Citing a mass of new information from the airline industry that must be 
studied, John Wayne Airport officials have again postponed public hearings on 
the proposed airline flight allocation plan. 
</P>
<P>
The initial hearing before the County Airport Commission, previously scheduled 
for tonight, now is set for Nov. 5, said Jan Mittermeier, assistant airport 
manager. She said county supervisors probably won't hold their public hearing 
and final vote on the plan until mid-November. 
</P>
<P>
Originally, the airport access plan -- which includes jet flight allocations at 
the tightly regulated airport -- was to have been approved in April. 
</P>
<P>
An unexpectedly slow review of the plan by the Federal Aviation Administration 
and opposition by two of the nation's major cargo carriers, Federal Express and 
United Parcel Service, upset that timetable, however. County airport officials 
met with the FAA on Monday and Tuesday to discuss the cargo carriers' concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
