<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: INTERNATIONAL KIDNAPING TRIAL OF COVINA MAN 
OPENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A well-to-do Covina chiropractor was described by a prosecutor at his 
international kidnaping trial as a man with a violent temper who threatened to 
kill a former girlfriend and her daughter to recover more than $100,000 in 
money and property he said he was owed. 
</P>
<P>
Rolando Peralta, 51, is on trial in Los Angeles federal court, accused of 
masterminding the kidnaping for ransom last June of a dental student in Mexico 
City in order to force her mother, Indiana Robleto, to pay Peralta the money he 
said he was owed. 
</P>
<P>
Peralta, his secretary, Socorro Contreras, and her boyfriend, Rigoberto 
Herrera, are charged with international hostage taking, conspiracy and 
extortion in the abduction of Maria Robleto, 22, who was released after a 
$40,000 ransom was paid. Robleto, a Maywood dentist, paid the ransom but it was 
unclear where the funds came from. 
</P>
<P>
Although the abduction occurred in Mexico, the case is being tried in federal 
court here because U.S. laws take precedence and because Peralta was arrested 
here. 
</P>
<P>
In opening statements to the jury, Assistant U.S. Atty. Carol Gillam said 
Peralta was a "vile-tempered" man who threatened to kill Indiana Robleto in 
telephone conversations with her that were secretly recorded by the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
But defense attorney Anthony Brooklier told jurors that Peralta was "set up" by 
Robleto because she hated him because of their failed love affair. He also 
argued that the abduction never took place, contending that Maria Robleto 
cooperated with her alleged kidnapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
