<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: FATHER, SON TO BE TRIED IN RECORD COCAINE 
BUST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A father and son team who allegedly oversaw the Mexican leg of a major 
Colombian smuggling ring were ordered Tuesday to stand trial in Los Angeles in 
connection with a record cocaine seizure at a Sylmar warehouse. 
</P>
<P>
After a preliminary hearing, federal Magistrate Lawrence Leavitt found probable 
cause to order Carlos Tapia Ponce, 68, and his son, Hector Tapia Anchondo, 38, 
held for trial in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
The two Mexican nationals were arrested Sept. 29 at the Flamingo Hilton Hotel 
in Las Vegas, one day after Drug Enforcement Administration agents raided the 
Sylmar warehouse and seized 21.4 tons of cocaine, the largest such seizure in 
history. 
</P>
<P>
Four men are being held in Los Angeles in the case. 
</P>
<P>
No date was set Tuesday for Tapia Ponce and Tapia Anchondo to appear on the 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
The government's sole witness at the preliminary hearing was DEA agent William 
Sherman, who testified that Tapia Ponce and Tapia Anchondo were identified as 
two key players in the massive drug smuggling operation. 
</P>
<P>
The identification was made by another man who was arrested in the case, James 
McTague, 41, who is married to Tapia Anchondo's sister. McTague, who was 
arrested along with three others on Sept. 28, has been identified as the 
manager of the Sylmar warehouse, where authorities found the cache of cocaine 
and $12.2 million in cash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
